definition: "Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) is a gonadotropin — a glycoprotein hormone produced by the anterior pituitary gland — that plays a central role in reproductive function in both sexes. In women, FSH drives the growth and maturation of ovarian follicles in the first half of the menstrual cycle (the follicular phase), stimulating the developing follicles to produce estrogen. As follicles mature and estrogen rises, FSH is normally suppressed through negative feedback. In men, FSH acts on Sertoli cells in the testes to support spermatogenesis. FSH secretion is regulated by GnRH from the hypothalamus, and is suppressed by estrogen and inhibin B (a hormone produced by granulosa cells in women and Sertoli cells in men that provides a direct measure of gonadal reserve). Rising FSH is the clearest and most reliable hormonal signal of declining gonadal reserve — in women, declining ovarian follicular reserve; in men, declining Sertoli cell function and impaired spermatogenesis."
why_it_matters: "For women, FSH is the primary laboratory signal of perimenopause and ovarian aging. As the ovaries age and the pool of remaining follicles diminishes, the follicles that remain are less responsive to FSH stimulation, and estrogen and inhibin B production per cycle declines. The pituitary compensates by producing more FSH, attempting to drive follicular development with escalating stimulatory pressure. This progressive FSH rise — beginning, on average, in a woman's late 30s or early 40s — is the earliest and most reproducible hormonal marker of the menopausal transition, often predating irregular cycles, hot flashes, or estrogen decline by years. FSH testing is essential context for any hormonal optimization work in perimenopausal women: it clarifies whether hormonal symptoms stem from the ovaries (high FSH indicates declining ovarian function) or from other axes (normal FSH with symptoms suggests other drivers). For men, elevated FSH in the context of infertility or low testosterone points to primary testicular failure rather than secondary (pituitary) hypogonadism — a distinction that determines whether fertility-preserving treatments are viable."

